<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911101-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>911101-0022.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Crestmont Financial Corp.:   Regulators Seek to Remove   Chairman of Sandamp;L Subsidiary</HL><DATE>11/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   CRES</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Crestmont Financial Corp., Edison, N.J., said federalregulators are seeking to remove the chairman of itsCrestmont Federal Savings andamp; Loan Association unit for &quot;unsafeand unsound practices.&quot;   A spokesman for the Office of Thrift Supervision inWashington confirmed that proceedings had begun againstLawrence B. Seidman, Cresmont Federal's chairman. The OTS, ina notice filed Wednesday, said Mr. Seidman &quot;engaged inimpermissible self-dealing, unsafe and unsound practices&quot; andbreach of fiduciary duty. Mr. Seidman sought to use hisposition as Crestmont's chairman to provide loan financingfor a New Jersey real estate development project he had aninterest in, the OTS charged. The OTS alleges that Mr.Seidman withheld information and realized a financial gainfrom his actions.</LP><TEXT>   Additionally, the OTS is seeking a cease and desist orderagainst Crestmont Federal executive vice president JohnBailey, who it said aided Mr. Seidman in his bid to obtainthe loan financing.   Crestmont, in a statement, said Mr. Seidman has agreed tocomply with an OTS order temporarily suspending him fromCrestmont Federal's chairmanship.   Crestmont said it wasn't charged in the actions againstthe two men. The two executives couldn't be reached forcomment.</TEXT></DOC>